Name: Empresa de Transporte Aéreocargo del Sur, S.A.
AKA:
Aerocargo del Sur Transportation Company
EMTRASUR
details.KeyFacts: On August 1, 2022, BIS issued a Temporarily Denial Order against Empresa de Transporte Aéreocargo del Sur, S.A. (a.k.a. "Aerocargo del Sur Transportation Company" and "EMTRASUR") (“Respondent”) for a period of 180 days in relation to the information indicating that the Respondent is a subsidiary of Consorcio Venezolano de Industrias Aeronauticas Y Servicios Aereos, S.A., (a.k.a. CONVIASA), a Venezuelan state-owned airline that was added to the list of SDN on February 7, 2020. In or around October 2021, the Respondent engaged in conduct prohibited by a BIS-issued temporary denial order against Iranian airline Mahan Air (a.k.a. "Mahan Airlines" and "Mahan Airways") and the Regulations by acquiring custody and/or control from Mahan Air of a U.S-origin Boeing 747 aircraft bearing manufacturer’s serial number 23413 (“MSN 23413”), an item subject to the EAR and classified under ECCN 9A991. In addition, the Respondent continued use of MSN 23413 on flights into Iran and Russia.

Name: Luis Fernando Gracia
details.KeyFacts:
On August 1, 2022, Luis Fernando Gracia (“Respondent”) agreed to 2-year denial order as part of a Settlement Agreement with BIS in relation to one violation of the Export Administration Regulations. Specifically, on or about August 28, 2018, the Respondent caused, aided, or abetted an attempted export from the United States to Mexico of 0A979 ballistic helmets and 0A987 rifle scopes, worth a total of $4,329, without the required BIS license (§ 764.2(b)).
In addition, the Respondent shall complete an internal audit of the export controls compliance program maintained by GE Equipos de Seguridad, which is located in Nogales, Arizona, and Sonora, Mexico. Further, the Respondent shall also complete export compliance training on the Regulations within twelve (12) months from the date of the Order.

Name: Ismael Gomez, Jr.
details.KeyFacts: On July 18, 2022, BIS issued a Denial Order against Ismael Gomez, Jr. ("Respondent") for a period of 10 years in relation to violations of 18 U.S.C. § 554(a). Specifically, the Respondent was convicted of fraudulently and knowingly exporting and sending or attempting to export and send from the United States to Mexico, one thousand and ten (1,010) rounds of .223 caliber ammunition. The Respondent was sentenced to 46 months in prison, three years of supervised release, and a $100 assessment.

Name: Scott Douglas Browning
details.KeyFacts: On July 18, 2022, BIS issued a Denial Order against Scott Douglas Browning ("Respondent") for a period of 7 years in relation to violations of Section 38 of the Arms Export Control Act. Specifically, the Respondent was convicted of willfully exporting and causing to be exported from the United States to the Netherlands defense articles, that is, Image Intensifier Generation 3 MX-10130, Image Intensifier Generation 3 MX-10160, Image Intensifier Generation 3 MX-11769, and the BAE Systems OASYS SkeetIR Micro Thermal Imaging Monocular 640x480, which are all designated as defense articles on the United States Munitions List, without having first obtained from the Department of State a license. The Respondent was sentenced to probation, $100 assessment, and $1,854,000 restitution.

Name: Hassan Ali Moshir-Fatemi
details.KeyFacts: On July 8, 2022, BIS issued a Denial Order against Hassan Ali Moshir-Fatemi ("Respondent") for a period of 10 years in relation to violations of the International Emergency Economic Powers Act. Specifically, the Respondent was convicted of knowingly and willfully conspiring and agreeing to export, reexport, and supply, and causing to be exported, reexported, and supplied, directly and indirectly, goods and services from the United States to Iran; and engaging in transactions for the purpose of avoiding and evading the Iranian Transaction Sanctions Regulations, including financing and facilitating transactions by foreign persons where such transactions are prohibited by United States law, without having first obtained from the Department of the Treasury. As a result of his conviction, the Court sentenced the Respondent to 12 months and one day imprisonment, three years of supervised release, a $100 assessment and a fine of $50,000.
